    1. Binomial Distribution¶

    🏛 Problem Statement¶

    The management of Lavista Museum has observed that 80% of visitors purchase souvenirs from the museum's gift shop.
    On the upcoming Sunday, a random sample of 10 visitors will be selected.

    We aim to determine:

    1. üéØ Exact Probability
      What is the probability that all 10 visitors in the sample will buy souvenirs?

    2. üìä Cumulative Probability
      What is the probability that at most 7 visitors in the sample will buy souvenirs?

    🔍 Why Use the Binomial Distribution?¶

    Before solving, let's verify that the conditions for applying a Binomial model are satisfied:

    1. ‚úÖ Two Possible Outcomes
      Each trial (visitor) can result in either:

      • Success: Visitor buys souvenirs
      • Failure: Visitor does not buy souvenirs

    2. ‚úÖ Fixed Number of Trials
      The sample size is fixed at ( n = 10 ) visitors.

    3. ‚úÖ Independence
      The purchase decision of one visitor does not affect the others.

    4. ‚úÖ Constant Probability of Success
      The probability of a visitor buying souvenirs remains constant at ( p = 0.8 ) for all trials.

    🧮 Model Representation¶

    Given these assumptions, the number of souvenir buyers ( X ) follows:

    $$ X \sim \text{Binomial}(n = 10, \, p = 0.8) $$

    Where:

    • ( n = 10 ) ‚Üí Number of visitors in the sample
    • ( p = 0.8 ) ‚Üí Probability a visitor buys souvenirs
    • ( X ) ‚Üí Number of visitors who buy souvenirs

    1.1 📐 Probability Function of the Binomial Distribution¶

    The probability mass function (PMF) of the Binomial Distribution gives the probability of observing exactly ( x ) successes in ( n ) independent trials, where ( p ) is the probability of success:

    $$ P(X = x) = {n \choose x} \, p^{x} \, (1-p)^{n-x} $$

    📌 Problem Parameters¶

    • ( n ) ‚Üí Number of visitors selected randomly: 10
    • ( p ) ‚Üí Probability of success (visitor buys souvenir): 0.80
    • ( q ) ‚Üí Probability of failure (visitor does not buy souvenir):
      ( q = 1 - p = 0.20 )
    • ( x ) ‚Üí Number of successes: 10

    🛠 Calculation Approach¶

    We will use binom.pmf() from scipy.stats to compute the probability that exactly ( x ) visitors (out of ( n = 10 )) buy souvenirs:

    Parameters¶

    n = 10 p = 0.80 x = 10

    Probability calculation¶

    probability_all_buy = binom.pmf(x, n, p) probability_all_buy

    📊 Probability of At Most 7 Successes¶

    From our earlier calculation, the probability of exactly 10 successes was approximately 0.11.

    Now, we want to find the probability of at most 7 successes ‚Äî
    that is, the probability that out of 10 randomly selected visitors, a maximum of 7 will buy souvenirs.

    🔍 Mathematical Definition¶

    We are looking for:

    $$ P(X \leq 7) $$

    Where:

    • ( X ) = Number of visitors (out of ( n = 10 )) who buy souvenirs
    • ( p = 0.80 ) = Probability that a visitor buys a souvenir

    📌 Using the Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF)¶

    The CDF of a random variable ( X ) is defined as:

    $$ F_X(x) = P(X \leq x) $$

    It gives the probability that ( X ) takes a value less than or equal to ( x ).

    🛠 Implementation with binom.cdf()¶

    We use binom.cdf() from scipy.stats to compute the cumulative probability:

    ```python from scipy.stats import binom

    Parameters¶

    n = 10 p = 0.80 x = 7

    Cumulative probability for X <= 7¶

    probability_at_most_7 = binom.cdf(x, n, p) probability_at_most_7

    🎨 Understanding plt.subplot(131)¶

    The plt.subplot() function in Matplotlib is used to arrange multiple plots within the same figure.

    📌 General Syntax¶

    plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, index)

    • nrows ‚Üí Number of rows of subplots in the figure.
    • ncols ‚Üí Number of columns of subplots in the figure.
    • index ‚Üí Position of the current subplot (counting from left to right, top to bottom, starting at 1).

    🔍 Shorthand Notation¶

    When written as plt.subplot(131), the three digits mean:

    • 1 ‚Üí One row of subplots.
    • 3 ‚Üí Three columns of subplots.
    • 1 ‚Üí Activate the first subplot (leftmost position).

    This is equivalent to writing plt.subplot(1, 3, 1).

    🖼 Interpretation¶

    Using plt.subplot(131) means that you are creating a 1 √ó 3 grid of subplots and working on the first one. You can then call plt.subplot(132) for the second plot and plt.subplot(133) for the third, arranging them side by side in a single row.

    📌 Conclusion¶

    From the plot, it is evident that the shape of the Binomial distribution is strongly influenced by the value of ( p ) (probability of success):

    • When ( p ) is low (close to 0), the distribution is skewed to the right ‚Äî most outcomes cluster near 0 successes.
    • When ( p ) is high (close to 1), the distribution is skewed to the left ‚Äî most outcomes cluster near ( n ) successes.
    • When ( p ) is around 0.5, the distribution becomes approximately symmetric, resembling a bell curve.

    This demonstrates how varying ( p ) changes both the center and spread of the distribution.

    2. Continuous Uniform Distribution¶

    🖥 Problem Statement — Debugging Time Analysis¶

    The IT industry keeps records of the time (in hours) required by a software engineer to fix a bug during the initial phase of software development.
    This information is stored in the file debugging.csv.

    📌 Definition of the Random Variable¶

    Let:

    $$ X = \text{Time needed to fix a bug (in hours)} $$
    • (X) is a continuous random variable because debugging time can take any real value within a range (not just discrete steps).

    🎯 Questions to Answer¶

    1. ‚è≥ Probability of Less Than 3 Hours
      Find (P(X < 3)): the probability that a randomly selected debugging task takes less than 3 hours.

    2. ‚åõ Probability of More Than 2 Hours
      Find (P(X > 2)): the probability that a randomly selected debugging task takes more than 2 hours.

    3. üìç 50th Percentile (Median)
      Find the median debugging time, i.e., the time (t) such that half of the debugging tasks take less than or equal to (t) hours: $$ \text{Median} = \operatorname{Quantile}_{0.50}(X) $$

    🔍 Next Steps¶

    • Step 1: Load the dataset and visualize the distribution of (X).
    • Step 2: Use the cumulative distribution function (CDF) to compute (P(X<3)) and (P(X>2)):
      $$ P(X<3)=F_X(3), \qquad P(X>2)=1-F_X(2) $$
    • Step 3: Use the inverse CDF (quantile function) to obtain the median:
      $$ \text{Median} = F_X^{-1}(0.5) $$

    📊 Histogram + Uniform PDF Overlay¶

    We will visualize the empirical distribution of debugging times and compare it to a Uniform model parameterized by the minimum and maximum observed times.

    🔧 Setup¶

    Let (X) be the debugging time (in hours).
    Using the sample:

    $$ \{x_i\}_{i=1}^n $$

    define:

    $$ a = \min_i x_i, \qquad b = \max_i x_i $$

    and model:

    $$ X \sim \text{Uniform}(a,b) $$

    with probability density function (PDF):

    $$ f_X(x) = \begin{cases} \dfrac{1}{b-a}, & a \le x \le b, \\[6pt] 0, & \text{otherwise.} \end{cases} $$

    Interpretation: Under this model, all times between (a) and (b) are equally likely.

    ✅ Notes¶

    • density=True in the histogram ensures it is on the same scale as the PDF.
    • If the histogram is too jagged, adjust bins (e.g., bins=20) for smoother visualization.
    • Large deviations between the histogram and the flat PDF line indicate that the uniform model may not be a good fit.

    📈 Recognizing a Uniform Distribution via Density Plot¶

    Another way to check if your data follows a uniform distribution is to inspect its density plot.
    For a truly uniform distribution, the density should be approximately flat between the minimum and maximum observed values.

    🔍 Approach¶

    We will use Seaborn‚Äôs distplot (or its modern replacement displot / histplot with kde=True) to visualize the distribution of debugging times.

    Let:

    $$ X = \text{Time needed for bug fixing (in hours)} $$

    If:

    $$ X \sim \text{Uniform}(a,b) $$

    then its probability density function is:

    $$ f_X(x) = \begin{cases} \dfrac{1}{b-a}, & a \le x \le b, \\[6pt] 0, & \text{otherwise.} \end{cases} $$

    📌 Interpretation¶

    • Flat density curve ‚Üí Suggests a uniform distribution.
    • Peaked or skewed curve ‚Üí Indicates some values occur more frequently than others, so the distribution is likely not uniform.

    üîπ Density plots are visual diagnostics. For formal confirmation, we need statistical tests.

    🧮 Understanding the Uniform PDF Calculation¶

    The above example demonstrates how to generate the probability density function (PDF) of a Uniform distribution using scipy.stats.

    1️⃣ Importing the Function¶

    The uniform distribution is imported from scipy.stats, which provides tools for probability distributions.

    2️⃣ Defining the Range of Values¶

    We consider 50 evenly spaced values between 1 and 5, representing possible values of the random variable ( X ).

    3️⃣ Uniform Distribution Parameters¶

    In the uniform PDF function:

    • loc = 1 ‚Üí the lower bound ( a ) of the distribution.
    • scale = 4 ‚Üí the width ( b - a ), so: $$ b = a + \text{scale} = 1 + 4 = 5 $$

    4️⃣ Probability Density Function¶

    The uniform PDF is given by:

    $$ f_X(x) = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{b-a}, & a \le x \le b \\ 0, & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} $$

    For ( a = 1 ) and ( b = 5 ):

    $$ f_X(x) = \frac{1}{4} = 0.25 \quad \text{for all } x \in [1,5] $$

    5️⃣ Output¶

    • x contains the 50 evenly spaced values between 1 and 5.
    • probs contains the constant PDF value ( 0.25 ) for each ( x ).

    🧮 Finding the Probability that Debugging Takes a Maximum of 3 Hours¶

    The Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF) of a random variable (X) gives the probability that (X) will take a value less than or equal to a specific (x):

    $$ F_X(x) = P(X \leq x) $$

    📌 Problem Context¶

    Here:

    • (X) = the number of hours required to debug the software.
    • We want:
    $$ P(X \leq 3) $$

    This is the probability that a randomly selected debugging process will take at most 3 hours.

    💡 Interpretation¶

    If we know the PDF (f_X(x)), then:

    $$ P(X \leq 3) = \int_{\text{lower bound}}^{3} f_X(t) \, dt $$

    If we already have the CDF (F_X(x)), then:

    $$ P(X \leq 3) = F_X(3) $$

    üìä Meaning:
    The value (F_X(3)) tells us the proportion of debugging processes that complete in 3 hours or less.

    🧮 Finding the Probability that Bug Fixing Takes More Than 2 Hours¶

    We are looking for:

    $$ P(X > 2) $$

    🔄 Complement Rule¶

    From probability theory:

    $$ P(X > 2) = 1 - P(X \leq 2) $$

    Since the CDF (F_X(x)) is defined as:

    $$ F_X(x) = P(X \leq x) $$

    We can write:

    $$ P(X > 2) = 1 - F_X(2) $$

    💡 Interpretation¶

    • If we have the CDF, simply evaluate (F_X(2)) and subtract from 1.
    • If we have the PDF (f_X(x)), compute:
    $$ P(X > 2) = \int_{2}^{\text{upper bound}} f_X(t) \, dt $$

    üìä Meaning:
    This probability represents the proportion of debugging tasks that require more than 2 hours to complete.

    🧮 Calculating the 50th Percentile (Median) of Debugging Time¶

    The 50th percentile is also known as the median.
    It is the value $x_{0.5}$ such that:

    $$ P(X \leq x_{0.5}) = 0.5 $$

    🔄 Relationship to the CDF¶

    The Percent Point Function (PPF) is the inverse of the Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF):

    $$ x_p = F_X^{-1}(p) $$

    Where:

    • $p$ is the probability (e.g., $0.5$ for the median).
    • $F_X^{-1}(\cdot)$ is the inverse CDF.

    💻 Using ppf() in Practice¶

    The median is obtained as:

    $$ x_{0.5} = F_X^{-1}(0.5) $$

    üìä Meaning:
    The 50th percentile tells us the typical debugging time ‚Äî half of all bug fixes are completed in less time, and half take longer.

    There is a 50% chance that a randomly selected software debugging requires less than three hours.

    There is a 75% chance that a randomly selected software debugging requires more than two hours.

    The 50th percentile of the software debugging time is 3 hours.

    3. Normal Distribution¶

    Problem statement¶

    🧮 SAT Exam 2020: Probability and Percentile Analysis¶

    A testing agency has collected SAT scores of 1000 students from the 2020 SAT exam (file: sat_score.csv).
    We aim to answer the following probability and percentile questions to assess the exam‚Äôs complexity.

    1️⃣ Probability of Scoring Less Than 800¶

    Let (X) be the SAT score of a randomly selected student.
    The probability of scoring less than 800 is:

    $$ P(X < 800) = F_X(800) $$

    Where (F_X(x)) is the CDF of SAT scores.

    2️⃣ Probability of Scoring More Than 1300¶

    Using the complement rule:

    $$ P(X > 1300) = 1 - F_X(1300) $$

    This gives the proportion of students who scored above 1300.

    3️⃣ Minimum Marks for the 90th Percentile¶

    The 90th percentile score (x_{0.90}) is found using the Percent Point Function (PPF), the inverse of the CDF:

    $$ x_{0.90} = F_X^{-1}(0.90) $$

    This is the score at which 90% of students score less, and 10% score more.

    4️⃣ Minimum Marks to Be in the Top 5%¶

    Similarly, the cutoff score for the top 5% of students is:

    $$ x_{0.95} = F_X^{-1}(0.95) $$

    This is the score at which 95% of students score less, and 5% score more.

    📊 Plotting the Distribution¶

    We will plot the empirical distribution of the data to analyze its shape and compare it to the Probability Density Function (PDF) of a Normal distribution. The parameters for the normal curve ‚Äî the mean (\mu) and standard deviation (\sigma) ‚Äî will be estimated directly from the data.

    For a normal distribution:

    $$ X \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2) $$

    the PDF is:

    $$ f_X(x) = \frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}} \, e^{-\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}} $$

    Overlaying this curve on the histogram allows us to visually assess how well the data follows a normal pattern ‚Äî if the data is approximately normal, the histogram should align closely with the bell-shaped curve defined by $\mu$ and $\sigma$.

    Standardization of Normal Variables¶

    Suppose we know that the SAT scores are normally distributed with a mean of 1000 and a standard deviation of 200 and ACT scores are normally distributed with a mean of 20 and a standard deviation of 5.

    A college provides admission only based on SAT and ACT scores. The college admin decides to give the top performer fellowship to the student who has performed the best among all applicants. The highest score received from applicants who appeared for SAT is 1350 and the highest score received from applicants who appeared for ACT is 30.

    Help the college to choose the best candidate for the fellowship!

    3.1 📏 Standardization of Normal Variables (SAT vs ACT)¶

    We compare top scores by converting them to standardized z-scores, which place scores on a common scale relative to their distributions.

    Given distributions:

    • SAT: $$X_{\text{SAT}} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu=1000,\ \sigma=200)$$
    • ACT: $$X_{\text{ACT}} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu=20,\ \sigma=5)$$

    Top observed scores:

    • SAT top score: $$x_{\text{SAT}} = 1350$$
    • ACT top score: $$x_{\text{ACT}} = 30$$

    Standardization formula: $$ z=\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma} $$

    Compute z-scores: $$ z_{\text{SAT}}=\frac{1350-1000}{200}=1.75 \qquad\qquad z_{\text{ACT}}=\frac{30-20}{5}=2.00 $$

    Interpretation:
    A larger $$z$$ indicates a performance farther above the mean relative to the distribution‚Äôs spread. Since $$z_{\text{ACT}}=2.00 > z_{\text{SAT}}=1.75$$, the ACT top score is more exceptional in standardized terms.

    ✅ Conclusion¶

    The ACT candidate (score 30) outperforms the SAT candidate (score 1350) on a standardized scale and should receive the fellowship.

    4. 📊 Central Limit Theorem (CLT)¶

    The Central Limit Theorem states that if we independently draw multiple samples from a population, calculate the mean of each sample, and plot these sample means, then the resulting distribution of sample means will approach a normal distribution as the sample size increases ‚Äî regardless of the shape of the population distribution.

    Mathematically, if:

    • Population mean: $\mu$
    • Population standard deviation: $\sigma$
    • Sample size: $n$

    Then the sampling distribution of the mean:

    $$ \bar{X} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \mu,\ \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} \right) \quad \text{as} \quad n \to \infty $$

    Key points:

    • Works for any original distribution (skewed, uniform, etc.) as long as samples are independent and identically distributed.
    • Larger (n) makes the sampling distribution more closely approximate normality.
    • The standard deviation of the sampling distribution ((\sigma_{\bar{X}})) decreases as (n) increases, improving the precision of the mean estimate.

    Let's watch CLT in action using a Python simulation¶

    Here is a Uniform Distribution (which is most definitely not Normal)¶

    🧪 Building a Sampling Distribution (n = 5, 500 samples)¶

    We will illustrate the Central Limit Theorem by constructing a sampling distribution of the mean:

    1. Draw a sample of size $n = 5$ (i.i.d. observations) from the population.
    2. Compute the sample mean for these 5 observations.
    3. Repeat steps 1‚Äì2 a total of 500 times to obtain 500 sample means (each based on $n=5$).

    🔍 What to observe¶

    • The histogram of these 500 sample means approximates a normal distribution, even if the underlying population is not normal.
    • The sampling distribution will be centered at the population mean $\mu$ and have standard error: $$ \sigma_{\bar{X}} = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{5}} $$
    • As the sample size (n) increases (e.g., 10, 30, 50), the sampling distribution becomes more tightly concentrated around $\mu$ and more nearly normal.

    ‚úÖ This experiment demonstrates the CLT: the distribution of sample means tends toward normality as (n) grows, regardless of the population‚Äôs original shape (assuming i.i.d. samples and finite variance).

    In [94]:
    Copied! 
    # set the seed for reproducibility
np.random.seed(1)
# set the sample size to 5
n = 5
# list to store sample means
sample_means = []
# iterate the loop to draw multiple samples
for j in range(500):
    # draw a sample of size n
    sample = np.random.choice(uniform_pop, size=n)
    # calculate the sample mean.
    sample_mean = np.mean(sample)
    # append the sample mean to the sample_means list
    sample_means.append(sample_mean)
# plot the histogram of sample means
sns.displot(sample_means, kde=True)
plt.title("Distribution of Sample Means for n = " + str(n))
plt.xlabel("sample mean")

    📌 Key Takeaway¶

    We have tested the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) using different population distributions. The results show that, regardless of the original shape of the population distribution, the distribution of sample means approaches a normal distribution as the sample size increases.

    Mathematically, for population mean $\mu$ and standard deviation $\sigma$, the sampling distribution of the mean for sample size $n$ is approximately:

    $$ \bar{X} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \mu,\ \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} \right) $$

    Larger (n) results in:

    • Greater normality in the shape of the sampling distribution.
    • Smaller spread due to the reduction in standard error ( \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} ).

    ‚úÖ Conclusion: The CLT ensures that the normal approximation for sample means is valid for sufficiently large (n), making it one of the most powerful concepts in statistics.

    5. 📍 Point Estimation¶

    Point estimation is the process of using sample data to calculate a single value (called a point estimate) that serves as the best guess for an unknown population parameter.

    For example:

    • The sample mean $\bar{x}$ is a point estimate of the population mean $\mu$.
    • The sample proportion $\hat{p}$ is a point estimate of the population proportion $p$.
    • The sample standard deviation $s$ is a point estimate of the population standard deviation $\sigma$.

    General idea: Given a random sample $x_1, x_2, \dots, x_n$, a point estimator $\hat{\theta}$ is a statistic used to approximate a population parameter $\theta$.
    The computed value $\hat{\theta}$ from the sample is the point estimate.

    Key property:
    Point estimates are single-number summaries and do not provide information about the uncertainty or variability of the estimate ‚Äî for that, we use interval estimation.

    🌲 Estimating the Population Mean Using the Sample Mean¶

    A non-profit organization sampled the files of the local forest department and recorded the damages (in thousands of dollars) for 10 wildfire incidents:

    $120,\ 55,\ 60,\ 10,\ 8,\ 150,\ 44,\ 58,\ 62,\ 123$

    The sample mean ($\bar{x}$) is the natural estimator of the population mean ($\mu$) when the data is a random sample.

    Formula for the sample mean: $$ \bar{x} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{n} $$

    Calculation: $$ \bar{x} = \frac{120 + 55 + 60 + 10 + 8 + 150 + 44 + 58 + 62 + 123}{10} $$ $$ \bar{x} = \frac{690}{10} = 69 $$

    ✅ Conclusion¶

    The estimated population mean damage is $69{,}000$. This value represents our best guess for the true average damage per wildfire in that area based on the sample data.

    In [107]:
    Copied!

sample = np.array([120, 55, 60, 10, 8, 150, 44, 58, 62, 123])

# find the mean of the sample
x_bar = np.mean(sample)
print(x_bar)
    # get the sample data sample = np.array([120, 55, 60, 10, 8, 150, 44, 58, 62, 123]) # find the mean of the sample x_bar = np.mean(sample) print(x_bar)
    69.0

    Insight¶

    • The estimate of the average amount of damages in wildfires in that area is $69000.

    Usually, the point estimate of an unknown population parameter is the corresponding sample statistic.

    For example:

    a. Population mean $\,\mu\,$ is estimated by the sample mean $\,\bar{x}\,$.

    b. Population median is estimated by the sample median $\,\tilde{x}\,$.

    c. Population proportion of success $\,\pi\,$ is estimated by the sample proportion of success $\,p\,$.

    6. 📊 Confidence Interval¶

    A confidence interval (CI) is a range of values, derived from sample data, that is likely to contain the true value of an unknown population parameter with a specified level of confidence.

    General form: $$ \text{Confidence Interval} = \text{Point Estimate} \ \pm\ \text{Margin of Error} $$

    Where:

    • Point Estimate ‚Üí the sample statistic (e.g., $\bar{x}$ for the mean)
    • Margin of Error ‚Üí depends on the desired confidence level and the standard error of the estimate

    Interpretation: A $95\%$ confidence interval means that if we took many random samples and computed a CI from each, approximately $95\%$ of those intervals would contain the true population parameter.

    Example for a mean with known $\sigma$: $$ \bar{x} \ \pm\ z_{\alpha/2} \cdot \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} $$ Here, $z_{\alpha/2}$ is the critical value from the standard normal distribution corresponding to the desired confidence level.

    Key points:

    • Higher confidence levels produce wider intervals.
    • Larger sample sizes produce narrower intervals (more precise estimates).

    Let's see how the confidence interval is constructed for the population mean when std dev is known¶

    It is rarely the case when you know the population standard deviation and not the mean. However, it may not be as unlikely an assumption as it seems. For a tight manufacturing process that is in place for a long time, the variability in the process may be controlled, but with small changes in temperature or humidity, the mean may change.

    Let's construct the confidence interval for an example where the population mean is unknown and the standard deviation is known.

    The caffeine content (in mg) was examined for a random sample of 50 cups of black coffee dispensed by a new coffee machine. The mean of the sample is found to be 110 mg. It is known that the standard deviation from all the machines of that manufacturer is 7 mg. Construct a 95% confidence interval for Œº, the mean caffeine content for cups dispensed by the machine.

    In [108]:
    Copied! 
    # import the required function
from scipy.stats import norm

# set the values of sample mean and sigma
x_bar, sigma = 110, 7

# set the value of sample size
n = 50

# construct the confidence interval
np.round(norm.interval(0.95, loc=x_bar, scale=sigma / np.sqrt(n)), 2)
    # import the required function from scipy.stats import norm # set the values of sample mean and sigma x_bar, sigma = 110, 7 # set the value of sample size n = 50 # construct the confidence interval np.round(norm.interval(0.95, loc=x_bar, scale=sigma / np.sqrt(n)), 2)
    Out[108]:
    array([108.06, 111.94])

    Insight¶

    • 95% of the time, the mean caffeine content for cups of coffee dispensed by the machine will be between 108.06 mg and 111.94 mg.

    Let's see how the confidence interval is constructed for the population mean when std dev is unknown¶

    The example discussed above is based on the assumption that the population standard deviation is known. However, in the majority of cases, that assumption will not be satisfied.

    When we do not know the population standard deviation, it can be estimated from the sample. In this case, the sample mean follows Student's t distribution with (n-1) degrees of freedom.

    Just like the normal distribution, t-distribution is also very useful in statistical inference. It is a symmetric distribution around 0. For a very large degrees of freedom, the t distribution is almost identical to the standard normal distribution. The parameter of t-distribution is known as degrees of freedom.

    Below is the graph of t-distribution for various degrees of freedom(k). We can notice that the distribution approximates normal as the value of k increases.

    In [109]:
    Copied! 
    # import the required function
from scipy.stats import t
from scipy.stats import norm

# set the values for x
x = np.linspace(-3, 3, 100)

# plot the t distribution for different values of k
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, sharex=False, sharey=False, figsize=(15, 10))
axes = axes.ravel()
for i, k in zip(range(6), [1, 2, 3, 5, 10, 30]):
    ax = axes[i]
    ax.plot(x, t.pdf(x, df=k), color="blue", label="t dist")
    ax.plot(x, norm.pdf(x), color="red", label="normal dist")
    ax.set_title("t-distribution for k={0}".format(k))
    ax.legend(loc="upper right", fontsize=10)
plt.tight_layout()
    # import the required function from scipy.stats import t from scipy.stats import norm # set the values for x x = np.linspace(-3, 3, 100) # plot the t distribution for different values of k fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, sharex=False, sharey=False, figsize=(15, 10)) axes = axes.ravel() for i, k in zip(range(6), [1, 2, 3, 5, 10, 30]): ax = axes[i] ax.plot(x, t.pdf(x, df=k), color="blue", label="t dist") ax.plot(x, norm.pdf(x), color="red", label="normal dist") ax.set_title("t-distribution for k={0}".format(k)) ax.legend(loc="upper right", fontsize=10) plt.tight_layout()

    ravel() is a NumPy function that flattens a multi-dimensional array into a 1-dimensional array. In the context of subplots, it's often used to convert a 2D grid of subplot axes into a 1D array for easier indexing.

    Let's use the t-distribution to construct the confidence interval for the mean when the population standard deviation is unknown.

    The caffeine content (in mg) was examined for a random sample of 50 cups of black coffee dispensed by a new machine. The mean of the sample is found to be 110 mg and the sample standard deviation is estimated to be 7 mg. Construct a 95% confidence interval for Œº, the mean caffeine content for cups dispensed by the machine.

    In [110]:
    Copied! 
    # import the required function
from scipy.stats import t

# set the values of sample mean and sample standard deviation
x_bar, s = 110, 7

# set the value of sample size and degrees of freedom
n = 50
k = n - 1

# construct the confidence interval
np.round(t.interval(0.95, df=k, loc=x_bar, scale=s / np.sqrt(n)), 2)
    # import the required function from scipy.stats import t # set the values of sample mean and sample standard deviation x_bar, s = 110, 7 # set the value of sample size and degrees of freedom n = 50 k = n - 1 # construct the confidence interval np.round(t.interval(0.95, df=k, loc=x_bar, scale=s / np.sqrt(n)), 2)
    Out[110]:
    array([108.01, 111.99])

    Insight¶

    • 95% of the time, the mean caffeine content for cups of coffee dispensed by the machine will be between 108.01 mg and 111.99 mg.

    Key Takeaways¶

    • The confidence interval for the population mean can be constructed for both cases when the population standard deviation is known and when it is unknown. The latter case is more common which demands the application of t-distribution with appropriate degrees of freedom.
    • The general approach to the construction of a confidence interval is to use the appropriate sample statistic to estimate the population parameter and use the proper percentile point of the sampling distribution.
